The Civil Rights Association issued a travel warning in Missouri
The National Association for African-American Civil Rights (NAACP) has issued a travel warning against Missouri due to discriminatory practices and racist attacks by the state.
“The NaaCP Missour travel bulletin enters into force on 28 August 2017 and calls on African-American tourists, visitors and locals to pay particular attention and to exercise extreme caution when travelling in a state where there have recently been a number of questionable racial events”, states the association’s press release.
The recent law in Missouri makes it difficult to bring cases of discrimination to justice, and the enforcement of state laws is disproportionate to minorities, which, according to the NAACP, led to the issuing of a travel warning.
"People's civil rights are being violated.
They will be stopped on the basis of skin color and abused or killed," said Rod Chapel, president of NAACP Missouri, to Kansas City Star.
"We've never heard of so many cases in such a short time."
The travel bulletin for Missouri is the first warning for the state of the United States of America.
The organization cited racist comments against African-American students at the University of Missouri and the death of 28-year-old black Tory Sanders from Tennessee.
Sanders died under questionable circumstances earlier this year, driving through the state when his car ran out of fuel, and the Missouri police arrested him even though he wasn't charged with a crime.
The travel bulletin also referred to the Missouri Attorney General’s report that the police are 75% more likely to stop a black driver than a white driver.
"The purpose of the travel bulletin is to encourage people to be alert and to warn their families, friends and colleagues about what might happen in Missouri," Chapel says.
"People must prepare themselves, for example, by including money for bail or by telling relatives that they intend to travel through the state."
According to the FBI, one hundred hate crimes were recorded in Missouri in 2015, the 16th highest in the United States.
The travel warning is also a response to Missouri's new law, which makes it difficult for companies to be sued for discrimination in housing and employment relationships.
Recently, ACLU, which defends civil rights guaranteed by the Constitution, issued travel warnings to Texas and Arizona after adopting immigration laws that oblige police to arrest people for immigration offences, which, according to the organization, increases racial profiling.
In general, travel warnings are issued by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and concern other countries, but recently they have been published by NGOs in response to certain laws and developments in the United States.
