Poverty and Death in Indonesia’s Goldland
Bardina Degei doesn't use the stove to cook.
He doesn't even use the kettle very often.
Degei lives in a wooden building in Enarotal, the capital of the Paniai region, located in the troubled province of Papua Indonesia.
After half an hour, the burnt sweet potato is devoured with bare, unwashed hands.
There is no furniture in Degei’s home. He sits on a muddy ground floor, where he usually takes care of his daily chores, such as washing in the muddy water from the nearby swamp.
The toilet office is provided by a bucket in a roofless room.
Degei is the youngest of her husband’s four wives and has not been assigned fields for treatment.
Polygamy is common here.
Working late can be dangerous: most of the village’s men are unemployed, and many drink a lot, and the soldiers must be taken into account.
"No one dares to walk into the village after five o'clock in the evening," Degei says.
This is a rare peek into everyday life in the Papua Highlands, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969, preceded by a controversial referendum, where 1,026 settlements were forced to vote publicly in front of the occupying forces.
The local independence movement, which opposed the Dutch rule, quickly turned its anger on the Jakarta regime, which keeps the region under strict control and prevents foreign journalists and human rights observers from entering it.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and Western Papua. The eastern part of the island belongs to Papua New Guinea.
Enarotali is secluded and bleak. The journey starts with an hour and a half flight from the province capital to Nabire, from Jayapura to Nabire, and continues on a belly-torn five-hour drive by a rental car.
There's no public transport here.
In a city of about 19,000 inhabitants, there are wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, the corrugated roofs of which have been dyed into yellow brown.
Only a few Indonesians have been here, not to mention journalists and foreigners.
Before the Christian missionaries arrived, the Papuan Mee Pago tribes worshiped the god Uga Tamee.
Other changes have taken place.
"We didn't have these clothes," Degei says. He means his colorful hand-woven sheath, dark skirt and brightly colored blouse.
"We used to have nothing but leaves covered in our bodies."
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, where 28 per cent of its inhabitants live below the poverty line, and infant mortality and illiteracy are among the highest in Asia.
But it's also Indonesian gold.
Paniai is about the size of a New Jersey highland area with 153 000 inhabitants, only about 100 kilometres from Pania is Grassberg, the world’s largest and most lucrative gold mine, owned by Freeport McMoran, based in Phoenix, U.S.A.
In 2015, the mine produced $3.1 billion in gold and copper for Freeport.
In addition, Papua has an estimated $78 billion in wood reserves.
For the Papuans, however, these riches bring misery, for they mean the repressive presence of a strong Indonesian army.
In 2005, the New York Times revealed that Freeport paid local military personnel and military local units nearly $20 million between 1998 and 2004, and that individual officers were paid up to $150,000.
Papua’s demands for greater self-determination threaten this source of income and are mercilessly silenced.
According to human rights activists, since 1969 the Indonesian army has killed over 500 000 Beans and raped, tortured and imprisoned thousands.
According to the Asian Commission on Human Rights, massacres in the highlands of the Papuan tribes in the 1970s were the proportions of genocide.
Last year, the Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 people in the area during peaceful demonstrations.
Brisbane Archdiocese’s report We Will Lose Everything from 2016 contains reports of the atrocities of the previous year, such as executions without trial, torture – rapes and electric shocks are particularly popular means – and ruthless attacks towards peaceful demonstrations.
"It is difficult to calculate the number of victims because there are weekly cases," says Andreas Harsono, Indonesian researcher at Human Rights Watch.
The screw has been tightened when Papua’s natural resources attract migrants from other parts of Indonesia.
Of the 3.5 million inhabitants of the province, 83% are Christians, but the population structure is changing when the Indonesian people from the islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawes move to the region in search of a better livelihood for Muslims.
Javan warung food stalls sell fried chicken and gado-gado-enhanced peanut sauce.
It's hard for the locals to compete.
"The movers have started selling chicken and vegetables in the market place cheaper than the locals," says 24-year-old Abeth You, who is from Pania and moved to the capital of the province after work.
"Local women lost their clients."
In his 2014 election campaign, President of Indonesia, Joko Widodo – nicknamed Jokowi – promised to address Papua’s injustices and human rights violations.
Papua is made up of 29 regions, and this former carpenter won the vote in 27 regions, including Pania, on his way to Jakarta Presidential Palace.
But little has changed in Papua, and the locals feel betrayed.
"Our hearts were broken because we voted for Jokow in 2014 and we expected him to fulfill our wishes and restore justice," you say.
The Panias experienced some kind of debacle just two months after Jokow’s inauguration in October.
Eleven children were singing Christmas songs by the fire at Enarotal on 7 December 2014 when two Indonesian soldiers appeared from the dark on motorcycles.
Scared kids told the soldiers they should use headlights.
According to local pastor Yavedt Tebai, the man returned with four soldiers.
