New results of age tests for asylum seekers in Sweden were published
The latest results of the medical age tests for asylum seekers in Sweden have been published. The results of the tests carried out with the new evaluation method reveal that more than 80% of those tested were determined to be over 18 years old, but not everyone believes that the tests are reliable.
The Swedish National Agency for Legal Medicine started testing earlier this year.
The tests will allow a more accurate assessment of the age of the asylum seeker, which was introduced after the Swedish Immigration Service was criticised for having failed to determine the actual age of applicants who claimed to be minors.
The Finnish Immigration Service has carried out 6,880 tests so far, and the Agency has now published the results of 2,481 tests. The tests were carried out between mid-March and the end of July 2017.
Eighty per cent of the tests, i.e. 2002 were determined to be over 18 years of age, and in 25 cases, the Agency determined that the test was “possibly 18 years of age or older”.
In 432 cases, it was concluded that the asylum seeker is "possibly under 18 years of age".
Tests were carried out only in cases where there was reason to suspect the age indicated by the applicant.
Johan Göransson of the Agency for Legal Medicine says that the results are consistent with the results of previous months.
"The figures are fairly consistent. There are no large differences in the statistics of previous months," he told The Local.
Although the majority of applicants were determined to be over 18 years of age, this does not necessarily mean that they have lied about their age.
In May, the Agency published the results of 581 tests and reported that 442 cases had "referencing that the subject was 18 years old or older".
When Svenska Dagbladet examined the same results, it turned out that in 243 cases the applicant had openly stated that he would be 18 years old this year.
The medical age assessment method used in the tests takes X-rays of the wisdom teeth and MRIs of the knee joints, then the images are analyzed by dentists and radiologists, and has also been criticised.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus, the Endocrinologist of the Karolinic Institute, whose work includes assessing the biological maturity of humans, to determine whether a person has become a teenager earlier than usual or later.
"I have had reason to think about it, and I believe that the method used is not the right one.
The determination of biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we are not sure how old we are, we should not pretend that we can do it," he said to Metro newspaper.
However, Göransson, the Agency for Legal Medicine, defended the accuracy of the tests: "You can generally say that the risk of determining a child as an adult is small.
The risk is highest in a situation where the test will soon be 18 years old, at which point the risk will be about 10%."
