In 2011, UEFA introduced fair play economic rules, which require PSG to be able to demonstrate that Neymar’s transfer has been financed without major losses.
EUR 222 million was paid to Barcelona for the closure of the Brazilian agreement, and Neymar’s annual salary for the new company moves in tens of millions of dollars.
The transfer of Neymar to France involves a wide range of economic considerations.
The PSG will have no difficulty paying Neymar's transfer amount and attaching him to its star guard, as the company will finance the dynasty of Qatar's oil-rich dynasty.
The clubs are allowed to spend large sums of money on the acquisition of players, but they must be balanced by real revenue sources in order to avoid loss-making football-related business.
The financial rules for fair play were drawn up at the initiative of Michel Platini, a Frenchman elected President of UEFA in 2007.
As a former footballer, Platini felt that the pursuit of success through debt was cheating and led to serious problems if banks or owners withdrew their support.
In 2011, the focus of fair play economic rules shifted from the debts of clubs to the monitoring of their losses.
The change meant that the business model used by Roman Abramovich for the first time in Chelsea in 2003 was significantly more difficult to implement. Abramovich bought a promising team, spent huge sums of money on player acquisitions and created a worldwide brand.
The current three-year evaluation period of fair play economic rules will run until 2018. During this period, clubs will be allowed to make losses of up to EUR 30 million.
Although Platini had to leave the UEFA president's duties in a scandalous manner in 2015, his successor, Alexander Ceferin, also wants to curb the reckless spending of the clubs.
"The rules for fair play are still in place and we will apply them in the future," Andrea Traverso, who is responsible for fair play financial rules in UEFA, told the Associated Press last week.
Although PSG paid Neymar out of his contract with a lump sum, it may amortise the amount in the accounts for the entire duration of his new contract.
Neymar has entered into a five-year contract, so the transfer amount can be recognised as a EUR 44.4 million annual expense over the next five years.
On the basis of fair play economic rules, the first sanctions were imposed in 2014. The biggest sanctions were imposed on PSG and Manchester City, which was financed by Abu Dhabi.
PSG received a fine of EUR 60 million, which was subsequently reduced to EUR 20 million. In addition, the club was ordered to limit its Champions League team to 21 players for the period 2014-2015 instead of the usual 25 players.
UEFA monitors clubs that may try to circumvent its financial regulations by increasing their income through companies linked to the club’s owners.
For example, if a company in Qatar supports PSG but the value of the aid is considered to be above the normal market level, UEFA does not calculate the aid as the actual result.
This was the case when UEFA decided in 2014 that the aid to PSG from the Qatar Tourism Authority was excessive.
It has also become clear that part of Neymar’s earnings in the PSG could be financed by the fees available to the Organisational Committee for the 2022 Football World Cup.
However, the PSG and the Organising Commission have prohibited Neymar from becoming an ambassador to the World Cup competitions. UEFA would be very easy to reveal such an arrangement.
As a result of the previous sanctions imposed by the PSG, UEFA will follow the rules even more closely than usual.
On Thursday, well-informed sources reported that UEFA did not negotiate a transfer of Neymar with PSG.
Sources gave an interview to the Associated Press on condition that their identity is not disclosed because they are not authorised to discuss the situation in the PSG.
According to the latest published financial statements, PSG’s net sales for the period 2015-2016 were EUR 542.4 million and operating profit exceeded EUR 10 million.
The financial statements for the last period have not yet been published.
PSG expects Neymar’s arrival to attract new sponsors and increase sales of companion products and jerseys.
The Society estimates that its turnover will increase by at least 30 % with the Neymar agreement.
The Spanish League, clearly irritated by the departure of one of the world’s best players, tried to make Neymar’s move more difficult, allegedly violating the economic rules of fair play.
"This is a clear economic case of doping, both for the club and for the state," said Javier Tebas, President of the Spanish League, to the Spanish newspaper AS, who referred to the qatarian ownership of the PSG.
Arsenal’s manager, Arsene Wenger, also has reservations about the state’s funding of the football club’s activities. Arsenal is owned by an American sportsman.
"The case is the result of ownership that has completely changed the football environment over the last 15 years," Wenger said on Thursday.
"Anything is possible after the state owns a football team.
It will be very difficult to comply with the financial rules of a fair game. There are so many interests related to the fact that the famous player represents the state."
