Bank of England keeps interest rates at 0.25%
The Bank of England is expected to announce that it will keep interest rates unchanged when economic growth has been unsettled and inflation has stopped speculation about interest rates.
The Bank of England has warned that economic growth will continue to be slow, and the bank moved interest rates because of the increasing pressure on family incomes.
The decision-makers of the Central Bank's Monetary Policy Commission decided, by 6 to 2, to keep interest rates at 0.25%, which this month gained less support because of the lack of economic growth.
In its quarterly inflation report, the Bank decreased its growth forecast to 1.7 per cent in 2017 and its forecast for 2018 to 1.6 per cent. It also warned that household income is under increasing pressure as inflation is expected to continue to accelerate by close to three per cent in the autumn.
However, according to the Bank, interest rate increases will be needed in the coming years to curb inflation boosted by Brexit, and the Bank announced that loan costs could have to be increased more than expected in the financial markets.
In addition, the members of the commission decided to withdraw part of the massive economic package that began a year ago in the aftermath of the Brexit referendum.
The Bank will close the Term Funding Scheme in February 2018, although it is now expected to provide preferential financing to banks in the form of a total of GBP 15 million, i.e. 115 million.
The report on the Bank's interest rate decision states: "According to the Financial Policy Commission forecast, the slow development of GDP will continue in the coming years as the decline in households' real income decreases consumption."
With regard to interest rates, the Bank reiterated the need for "some degree of tightening of monetary policy" in order to curb inflation "a little wider than the market's expectations".
The market is currently predicting the first increase in the third quarter of 2018 and the second in 2020.
However, the Bank stressed that the possible increases are "scale" and "limited".
In May, the Bank predicted an increase of 1.9 per cent for this year and an increase of 1.7 per cent for next year.
It now kept its growth forecast for 2018 at 1.8%.
The weight weakened against the dollar and the euro as a result of the news.
Compared to the dollar, the pound weakened by 0.5 per cent, amounting to $1.31, which weakened by 0.4 per cent compared to the euro and amounted to EUR 1.11.
The decision to keep interest rates unchanged was taken after weaker than expected growth rates were dampened by increased expectations of interest rates. GDP grew by 0.3 per cent in the second quarter and by 0.2 per cent in the first quarter.
The Bank expects growth to remain at 0.3 per cent in the third quarter but to pick up slightly at the end of the year.
Its latest inflation review gave little hope to households suffering from rising inflation and low wage increases, and the bank says that the situation will deteriorate even before it improves.
The Bank added that monetary policy "cannot prevent" falling income over the next few years, but expects wage developments to recover "significantly" at the end of the three-year forecast period.
The economy will also be strengthened by the strong growth in demand for British products as a result of the weak pound, which will reverse some of the effects of the fall in private consumption.
The decision was taken one year after the fall in interest rates to 0.25% after the shock of the EU referendum, which led to a fall in the pound.
The Bank estimates that the overall impact of the decision will probably not be reflected in prices and the economy until four years later.
Prior to the recent decision of the Central Bank, the demand for interest rate increases had become ever louder as inflation tightened the pressure on households, and three decision-makers demanded a 0.5% interest rate increase in July.
Inflation eased last month to 2.6 per cent from 2.9 per cent in June, but according to the bank, it was expected and inflation will increase again in the coming months.
According to the Bank, the excess of its 2% target was 'all' due to a weak pound.
