NHS prescribes 10 000 controversial anti-HIV medicines
As of September, patients can be prescribed a "returnable" anti-HIV medicine, and the dispute over the funding of the medicine in the UK public health system (NHS) was concluded in the Supreme Court.
NHS reported that pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is prescribed to approximately 10 000 people during the first three-year trial. Prior to sexual intercourse, a drug has been found to reduce the risk of infection by approximately 86% in high-risk individuals.
NHS agreed to finance the experiment after the Court of Appeal upheld last year’s Supreme Court ruling, which states that NHS is able to pay for the PrEP medicine, even though it claims that it should be financed by local authorities.
Simon Stevens, director of NHS England, called the decision announced on Thursday "significant new intervention", and the national AIDS organization described it as "a crucial moment".
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield are the first to accept registrations for an experiment that will expand to other clinics in October. The experiment will reach its full scope in England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) should be taken before intercourse with an HIV medicine that reduces the risk of infection.
Tests have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV infection in risk groups.
A medicine to be taken before sexual intercourse means that there are enough drugs in the body during sexual intercourse to prevent HIV infection.
You can take it every day or two hours before you have sex.
The treatment target group includes gay men, bisexual men and transgenders as well as people with HIV-positive partners who are not receiving effective treatment.
The clinics select candidates who qualify for the trial from men, women and transgenders as well as those whose HIV-positive partner is not known to receive antiretroviral treatment for his or her disease.
People living in England and registered for general medical treatment can also apply for an experiment at their local sexual health clinic.
The programme costs GBP 10 million, and this week the UK NHS signed a contract for medicines after an international call for tenders.
The purpose of the trial is to assess the potential of PrEP by collecting extensive clinical evidence of its targeting, uptake and implementation.
"This significant new intervention should complement and enhance the existing diverse and more effective ways of preventing HIV," says Stevens.
"It's yet another major achievement in the struggle for more than 30 years to solve one of mankind's greatest health challenges."
"This is a crucial moment in the fight against HIV", says Deborah Gold, Director of the National AIDS Organization.
"If PrEP is applied correctly to those who need it and to those at risk, it may have a revolutionary effect on the British HIV epidemic.
From September onwards, those at risk will receive a medicine that will be used independently without the need to negotiate with a partner, through a test funded by NHS, and will have a empowering effect that will improve the lives of a very large number of people.
This was welcome news."
"The most important thing now is to ensure that the experiment is launched quickly throughout the country and that no one in the risk group is excluded," says Ian Green, Director of Terrence Higgins Foundation.
"The PrEP medicine used in the experiment has been acquired and we will soon be able to protect ten thousand people at risk from HIV infection."
"The launch of the PREP experiment is a welcome event, which has been delayed in vain for several months due to the slowness of the government," says Sharon Hodgson, Minister of Health of the Shadow Government.
"We have evidence that the medicine can have a revolutionary effect on our work to prevent HIV and stop the spread of this threatening disease.
The experiment will help us to better understand the real benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that the experiment is launched as soon as possible throughout the country, so that we can protect those who are exposed to HIV and get one step closer to the situation where the spread of HIV in society has been successfully stopped."
