Origin of comic book: Story of a castle
The small Scotney Castle in the county of Kent is now known as the Squeeze music video and Margaret Thatcher's hideout from the 1970s and 1980s.
But it has 700 years of turbulent history. Now, in a charming place in the Bewl River Valley, this castle is the subject of a comic book written by Jamie Rhodes, an author with moped hair in old documents.
"I love being able to study the text written by a person who died over 300 years ago," Rhodes says in a longing.
"I feel a personal connection when I hold the letter in my hand."
Rhodes book, A Castle in England, tells the stories of families living in Scotney from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian era. Each story is illustrated by a different artist, a promising British cartoonist: Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer or Isabel Greenberg.
This is not Rhodes' first book based on archives. In 2014, he appeared Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories, whose inspiration was based on documents from the British National Library. The project was emotional.
"I went to tears when I noticed a thumbprint in the letter. The letter was written by a double agent who worked for Jacobites in the 1700s", Rhodes says.
"It was his fingerprints!
And the letters smell like smoke, because then fire was used as lighting.
Three centuries later, the smell makes the reader feel that he is on the spot.
I love archives!"
An old writer who was attracted to documents was allowed to live in the castle for almost four months with the support of the National Trust Foundation and the National Art Council in England, which seemed too good to be true. He admits that he could not stay in the castle without delay a little longer than would have been desired.
He spent days studying the Victorian "new" castle, archives, treasures and raritys, such as hyena heads hung on the walls and bottles in the moat for centuries.
He wandered around the ruins and lands of the old castle and talked with forest rangers, gardeners and sometimes illustrative artists.
In the evenings, he "took whiskey and started writing."
The closer history of Scotney is rather unknown, since the castle was transferred entirely to the National Trust Foundation only after the death of the last heir, Elizabeth Hussey, in 2006.
When Rhodes arrived about ten years later, the Foundation’s staff were only just starting to look through the archives. Rhodes describes that the archives had been held for hundreds of years using the same method: taking everything extra to the attic.
The archives contained journals, letters from the times of the English Empire and maps of who owned what. "You could imagine that ground disputes are boring," Rhodes says. "However, families fought here for even one birch.
I thought, "Let's give it a rest."
Some of the stories in the book go from the castle to the history of England, such as The Labourer. It tells of a man who soon after the castle was completed, joined the British peasant monkey in 1381.
"Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex says there was a riot in the castle in 1380," Rhodes says.
"The English peasant monkey began in the same area, and it occurred to me that the rebellion could start a riot.
"Maybe these events are connected?"
Other stories in the book are closely related to the history of the castle – such as The Priest, the story of the priest that the Darrell family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
The Smuggler, on the other hand, tells the story of the smuggler Arthur Darrell in the 18th century. He is said to have staged his own funeral with stones filled with stones (it was discovered years later when his tomb was opened).
The Darrells are Rhodes' favorite family in Scotney. "The family's men seem to have been quite a bunch of guys, and they've been in debt all the time, buying things they couldn't afford.
The Darrell family men solved their debt problems by marrying wealthy old women, and I see them as handsome friends who knew how to court the heiress."
Now Rhodes is looking for new writing experiences.
He spent two weeks in Finland writing a comic book about Lifeinmäki, a sanatorium in the early 20th century, where only a eutrophic plot remains.
Scotney Castle has a special place in his heart.
"It was sad to leave," he says.
