Red meat, dairy products and chocolate may relieve irritable bowel syndrome
Red meat and chocolate may sound like nightmares in the digestive system.
However, a recent study claims the opposite: a diet rich in meat protein and dairy products may facilitate irritable bowel syndrome.
Irritable bowel syndrome is an incurable disease that affects about 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 people in the United Kingdom, causing abdominal cramps, swelling, recurrent or bloody diarrhoea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Those suffering from irritable bowel syndrome are generally advised to avoid meat and dairy products. However, researchers at Washington University found that the essential amino acid tryptophan contained in the protein helps the body develop immune cells that strengthen the intestinal tolerance.
According to the director of the study, Marco Colonna, immune cells guard the swamp and ensure that harmful microbes that hide in the food do not enter the body.
Cells that balance the cells that cause inflammation, which strengthen tolerance, protect the body without damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance falls too close to inflammation, irritable bowel syndrome may result.
Tests showed that immune cells that strengthen tolerance are present in mice with specific bacteria in their intestines.
The bacteria in question need tryptophan to make immune cells appear. Tryptophan is one of the ingredients used to build proteins.
"We discovered the connection between Lactobacillus reuteri and the development of cells that promote tolerance. Lactobacillus reuteri is part of normal intestinal microorganisms," says Professor Colonna.
"The more tryptophan in the mouse's diet, the more immune cells they had."
If it works in humans, the combination of Lactobacillus reuteri and a diet rich in tryptophan can strengthen intestinal tolerance and reduce inflammation sensitivity.
In examining immune cells that strengthen tolerance, researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barragan found that although one mouse group had such cells, they were not present in mice of the same mouse species that were kept separate from the other group.
He suspected that the difference was related to the microbes in the mice’ intestines, i.e. the normal gastrointestinal community of bacteria, fungi and viruses.
When the intestinal DNA of mice was examined, six species of bacteria were found in mice with immune cells but not in other mice.
When Lactobacillus reuteri was administered to mice that grew in a sterile environment without intestinal microorganisms and did not develop immune cells, they began to develop immune cells.
Scientists wanted to find out how the bacteria affected the immune system. They raised Lactobacillus rheteric bacteria in fluid and transferred small amounts of fluids — without bacteria — to immature immune cells isolated from mice.
The immune cells developed into cells that enhance tolerance.
When the active ingredient was purified from the liquid, it proved to be a by-product of the metabolism of tryptophan known as indole-3 lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in mouse food, the number of cells that boost tolerance increased by about 50 percent. When the tryptophan count was halved, the number of cells decreased by half from before.
According to Cervantes-Barragan, man has the same tolerance cells as the mouse, and most of us have Lactobacillus rheuteri bacteria in our digestive tract.
It is not yet known whether tryptophan by-products of Lactobacillus reuteri make cells develop in humans in the same way as in mice. However, in patients with irritable bowel syndrome, there have been genetic defects associated with tryptofan.
