The White House exhibit cost thousands of dollars to taxpayers.
The White House's decision last month to fly a Navy helicopter to the South lawn of the White House was to pay taxpayers $24,000 for an American production event.
The green and white Sikorsky VH-3D helicopter is known as Marine One when the President is on board. It was an attraction at an event held in the White House on 17 July 2017 where American building programs were presented.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and a number of White House officials visited the products from all 50 states.
In addition to the helicopter produced in Connecticut, there was a sailing boat from Maine, a fire engine from Wisconsin and a forklift from Mississippi.
The White House military office had requested a helicopter to be present only about 36 hours before its landing on the southern lawn for an "exceptional" event, as shown in the Navy HMX-1 helicopter fleet records.
"I just wanted to make sure you're aware of this because it's an exceptional event with a lot of visibility," the HMX-1 commanding officer wrote in an e-mail to his supervisor, who is the Deputy Commandant of the Navy Air Force.
The message said that the helicopter would arrive on the southern lawn at 17 July 7 in the morning and the event would start at 3 in the afternoon. The helicopter would not leave until the lawn field was cleared between 6 and 9 in the evening.
In addition, the message mentioned that if a helicopter were to be delayed from the White House, another crew would be needed due to the restrictions on service periods.
The original crew was in the helicopter during the incident, and the unit’s security personnel were at the helicopter when it was on the ground.
It is not clear from the documents received by TIME magazine whether another crew was eventually needed.
The Hatch Act of the United States prohibits federal workers from using government property for political purposes.
According to the documents, HMX-1 asked if the event was a violation of the law.
"One of our questions was whether this was a violation of the Hatch Act.
"It sounds like you can attend," said the Deputy Commandant.
Made in America was an official White House event, so it was not covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political tone.
At the event, the President spoke out in favour of the reform of health care and of the looser state regulation that was before the Senate at the time.
The use of Marine One helicopter and Air Force One for political purposes is not a new phenomenon.
The presidents have to use them on their travels.
but their use only for photographs is unusual.
Trump’s actions attracted attention in February when Air Force One rolled the president’s campaign event in Melbourne, Florida. Trump has strongly criticised the use of his predecessor’s presidential aircraft on Twitter.
"The White House is very pleased with Made in America, where products made by American workers from all 50 states were presented," said White House Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 crews regularly conduct training flights in the Washington area and train on the southern lawn to bring the president to the White House with an accuracy of one centimetre.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany at the beginning of July, HMX-1 made 58 training landings for the White House.
According to one official, flights to Made in America included a monthly crew training quota.
The unit’s helicopters also flew 11 hours on that day in “non-presidential support” missions.
According to the White House, there was no other cost to taxpayers.
Sikorsky’s publicist reported that the company was not involved in organising a helicopter demonstration on the south lawn of the White House.
HMX-1 has no records of flights related to the President's duties, and it is difficult to accurately estimate the costs of the event.
According to the Ministry of Defence's 2017 hourly fees, the VH-3D helicopter's compensation rate is $24,380 per flight hour.
According to HMX-1's records, flights from Quantico Base to and from the state of Virginia to the White House took a total of one hour.
According to the White House, the cost of operating the helicopter is clearly lower.
"It is misleading to calculate the costs for tax payers according to the level of compensation," says Walters.
"The estimated level of compensation includes staff, maintenance and many other so-called embedded costs, which are taken into account in the annual budget."
According to a study carried out by the RAND research company in 2015, compensation levels do not include personnel costs, but take into account fuel, maintenance and contract costs.
At the time of the incident, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of helicopters at the event.
"The idea is to introduce American production," Spicer said.
"I know that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud that they are involved in ensuring national security and thereby employ probably hundreds or thousands of people.
And I think that, like most Americans, we are proud of the helicopter and other defence equipment that many Americans have worked hard for.
It is entirely appropriate to bring it up."
It is not certain whether Trump was in the helicopter during the event, but at least he sat down for the driver of the fire truck.
